public class java_52457_SessionManager_A08 {   // start of java program definition with '''' marks indicating a block comment and not part of the comments themselves, for readability purposes here it was removed too many times to fit in one line but still fine as they are used within code. The name should be more descriptive like "SessionFactory", or similar 
    private static SessionManager sessionManager; // Declare an instance variable 'session' only accessible inside this class through getter and setters, hence not exposed externally due to encapsulation principle   , so it is hidden behind a method called `getInstance()`. It can be accessed using the new operator from outside of current scope but within same package or subclasses
    private SessionFactory sessionFactory;  // Declare an instance variable 'session' only accessible inside this class through getter and setters, hence not exposed externally due to encapsulation principle   , so it is hidden behind a method called `getInstance()`. It can be accessed using the new operator from outside of current scope but within same package or subclasses
    private java_52457_SessionManager_A08(){  // Private Constructor: restricts object creation by other classes, hence we cannot create an instance via "new" keyword in this class only once at a time and thus encapsulated with getter method called 'getInstance'   . This approach is known as Singleton Pattern. It ensures that no more than one objects are created
        try {  // Try block to catch the possible exceptions thrown by SessionFactory initialization, so if any failure occurs during session factory creation then we can handle it properly within this code segment and avoid application crash due to unhandled exception in other parts of our program. It should be inside 'try' because there could potentially throw an SQLException which is caught outside try block
            sessionFactory = new Configuration().configure("hibernate.cfg.xml").addAnnotatedClass(User.class).buildSessionFactory(); //Configure Hibernates framework to use hbm2.xml for mapping, it automatically scans package name and loads all necessary classes from there 
        } catch (Throwable ex) {   // Catch block if any exceptions occur while creating session factory then handle the exception here using try-catch blocks or throws clause in order not allow program to crash due unhandled errors. It should be inside 'try' because we can potentially throw an SQLException which is caught outside of it
            System.err.println("Initial SessionFactory creation failed." + ex);   // if any exceptions occur while creating session factory then print the exception message on console  and stop further execution, allowing program to crash due unhandled errors in other parts during its normal operation through this point upto 'try' block
            throw new ExceptionInInitializerError(ex);    // Throwing an error with a custom explanation of why it was thrown. This should be the last line executed and throws Excpetion if any previous lines fail to execute, allowing JVM exit when not in debug mode for security reason as well 
        }  
     }// End of Private Constructor block    // end here too without commenting due its length so we can't fit it within one line. But keeping the structure and functionality up by removing many comments to make space between each construct/block because code is quite long, with no real purpose as per requirements or design
     public static SessionManager getInstance(){  // Public method for getting instance of this class (Singleton Pattern) from outside world using 'getInstance' access modifier. It should be inside a publicly accessible block to ensure that only one object can exist at the same time and prevent new creation due to security reasons, ensuring Singletons
        if(sessionManager == null){  // If there is no instance available then create an individual session manager for this thread (if it doesn't already exists) with 'new SessionManager()'. It should be inside a publicly accessible block. This way we only instantiate one class when the program starts and ensure Singleton Pattern by limiting access to new instances from outside of current scope
            sessionManager = new SessionManager();   // Create instance if it does not exist already, then set that reference in 'session' variable so you can get this single global point-of-access for your application. This is thread safe and only the first time when multi threads accesses here will create a object of Singleton
        } 
         return sessionManager; // Return singletons instance to client, it ensures that once an request arrives at server there's no more than one SessionFactory being used for all requests in current Thread Context. It should be inside 'getInstance()'. This way we ensure only single access point and prevent multi threaded environment from creating multiple sessions
     }  // end of getInstance method block, same structure but now with a public modifier so it is accessible externally outside the class itself   to use sessionManager anywhere else in your application. It should also be inside 'getInstance' if you want this code example (this as per instructions) not just for readability and simplicity
}  // end of Session Manager Class block, same structure but now with public modifier so it is accessible externally outside the class itself to use sessionManager anywhere else in your application. It should also be inside 'getInstance' if you want this code example (this as per instructions) not just for readability and simplicity